---
import PageShell from '../../../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'Overview', level: 2 },
  { id: 'why-croatia', text: 'Why Retirees Choose Croatia', level: 2 },
  { id: 'visa-residency', text: 'Visa & Residency', level: 2 },
  { id: 'insurance-requirements', text: 'Insurance Requirements', level: 2 },
  { id: 'recommended-providers', text: 'Recommended Providers', level: 2 },
  { id: 'healthcare-access', text: 'Healthcare Access', level: 2 },
  { id: 'costs', text: 'Cost Planning', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Croatia Insurance Guide', href: '/countries/croatia/insurance' },
  { title: 'Digital Nomad Visa Croatia', href: '/visas/digital-nomad-visa/in/croatia' },
  { title: 'Senior Insurance', href: '/best/senior-insurance' },
  { title: 'Europe Insurance', href: '/best/europe-insurance' },
  { title: 'Portugal for Retirees', href: '/insurance-for/retirees/in/portugal' },
];

const providerColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'ageLimit', header: 'Max Entry Age' },
  { key: 'preExisting', header: 'Pre-Existing' },
  { key: 'croatiaNetwork', header: 'Croatia Network' },
  { key: 'monthly', header: 'Monthly (Age 60)' },
];

const providerRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', ageLimit: '74', preExisting: 'Covered (24mo wait)', croatiaNetwork: 'Good', monthly: '$320-480' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', ageLimit: '74', preExisting: 'Moratorium option', croatiaNetwork: 'Excellent', monthly: '$300-450' },
  { provider: 'Bupa Global', ageLimit: '65 (new)', preExisting: 'Full underwriting', croatiaNetwork: 'Good', monthly: '$350-520' },
  { provider: 'IMG Global', ageLimit: '74', preExisting: 'Case-by-case', croatiaNetwork: 'Adequate', monthly: '$240-380' },
];

const costColumns = [
  { key: 'item', header: 'Expense' },
  { key: 'monthly', header: 'Monthly' },
  { key: 'notes', header: 'Notes' },
];

const costRows = [
  { item: 'International Insurance (55-59)', monthly: '$250-380', notes: 'Comprehensive coverage' },
  { item: 'International Insurance (60-64)', monthly: '$320-480', notes: 'Comprehensive coverage' },
  { item: 'International Insurance (65-69)', monthly: '$420-620', notes: 'Comprehensive coverage' },
  { item: 'HZZO (Public System)', monthly: '€50-80', notes: 'Via voluntary enrollment' },
  { item: 'Local Croatian Insurance', monthly: '€80-150', notes: 'Croatia/EU coverage' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Health Insurance for Retirees in Croatia | Residency Guide 2026"
  description="Complete guide to health insurance for retirees moving to Croatia. EU residency options, HZZO public healthcare, costs, and insurance options for American and European retirees on the Adriatic."
  headline="Health Insurance for Retirees in Croatia"
  subheadline="Croatia offers Mediterranean lifestyle, EU membership, and affordable living. Since joining Schengen and adopting the Euro, retiring here got simpler. Here's how to handle healthcare and insurance."
  heroImage="/images/countries/default-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Retiree Quotes"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna"
>
  <p class="text-sm text-neutral-500 mb-4">
    <strong>Affiliate disclosure:</strong> We may earn a commission when you click our links and purchase insurance. This doesn't affect our recommendations or the price you pay.
  </p>

  <h2 id="overview" class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Overview</h2>

  <p class="mb-4">
    Croatia has emerged as an underrated retirement destination. The Dalmatian coast rivals Italy and Greece for beauty—at 30-40% lower costs. EU membership since 2013, Euro adoption in 2023, and Schengen entry in 2023 have transformed it from bureaucratic challenge to accessible option.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-4">
    This guide covers what retirees need to know: residency pathways, insurance requirements for the application process, healthcare system access, and how costs compare to other Mediterranean options.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 mb-8">
    <h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-3">Key Facts for Retirees</h3>
    <ul class="space-y-2">
      <li><strong>EU member:</strong> Yes (since 2013)</li>
      <li><strong>Currency:</strong> Euro (adopted January 2023)</li>
      <li><strong>Schengen:</strong> Yes (joined January 2023)</li>
      <li><strong>Insurance required:</strong> Yes, for temporary residence permit</li>
      <li><strong>Public healthcare:</strong> HZZO available via voluntary enrollment</li>
      <li><strong>Cost of living:</strong> 30-40% lower than Western Europe</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="why-croatia" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Why Retirees Choose Croatia</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Stunning Adriatic Coast</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Dubrovnik, Split, Zadar, and the islands (Hvar, Korčula, Brač) offer Mediterranean beauty without Mediterranean prices. Crystal-clear water, ancient walled cities, island-hopping by ferry. The coastline rivals Greece and Italy for scenic retirement.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Affordable EU Living</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    A comfortable retirement in Croatia costs €1,500-2,500/month including housing. That's 30-40% less than similar quality in Spain or Portugal, 50% less than Italy or France. Dubrovnik is pricier; Split and smaller towns offer better value. Real estate is reasonable, especially inland.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Full EU Integration</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Since 2023, Croatia offers the best of EU membership: Euro (no currency risk), Schengen (easy travel throughout Europe), and EU healthcare coordination. Your EHIC/GHIC card works here. For EU citizens, residency is straightforward. For non-EU citizens, clear pathways exist.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Safe and Welcoming</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Croatia is very safe with low crime rates. The culture is welcoming to foreigners—tourism is a major industry, and locals are accustomed to visitors. English is widely spoken in tourist areas and by younger generations. German and Italian are also common.
  </p>

  <h2 id="visa-residency" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Visa & Residency</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">For EU/EEA Citizens</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    EU citizens have automatic right to live in Croatia. Register with local police within 30 days of arrival. After 5 years continuous residence, you can apply for permanent residency. No visa, no income requirements, no insurance mandates beyond normal EU coordination.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">For Non-EU Citizens</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Non-EU retirees apply for a temporary residence permit based on "other reasons" (retirement) or family reunification. Requirements include: proof of sufficient funds (approximately €4,000 in savings plus €600/month income), health insurance valid in Croatia, and accommodation proof.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Digital Nomad Visa Option</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Croatia's Digital Nomad Visa (1 year) could work for retirees with ongoing consulting income or remote work. Requires €2,540/month income and health insurance. It's designed for workers, not pure retirees, but the line is flexible if you have any income-generating activity.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Timeline</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Apply at Croatian embassy before arrival or at local police station within 90 days of visa-free entry. Processing takes 30-60 days typically. Initial permit valid 1 year, renewable. After 5 years, eligible for permanent residence.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Need Residency Insurance?"
    description="Get coverage that meets Croatian temporary residence requirements."
    buttonText="Get Croatia Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <h2 id="insurance-requirements" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Insurance Requirements</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">For Residency Application</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Non-EU citizens applying for temporary residence must show proof of health insurance valid in Croatia. The coverage must be comprehensive—travel insurance typically doesn't qualify. International health insurance from major providers meets requirements. Once resident, you can transition to Croatian public or private options.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">What to Look For</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    For retirees, prioritize: comprehensive inpatient and outpatient coverage, EU-wide coverage (for travel within Schengen), emergency evacuation, and pre-existing condition coverage if needed. Croatia's hospitals are decent but limited for complex cases—evacuation to Vienna or Munich may be necessary.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Pre-Existing Conditions</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Cigna offers guaranteed acceptance with 24-month waiting period. Allianz offers moratorium underwriting—pre-existing conditions excluded initially, covered after 2 years symptom-free. Once enrolled in HZZO (Croatian public system), all conditions are covered.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">After Establishing Residency</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Once resident, you can voluntarily enroll in HZZO (Croatian Health Insurance Fund) for approximately €50-80/month. This provides access to the public system. Many retirees maintain international coverage alongside HZZO for private options and travel coverage.
  </p>

  <h2 id="recommended-providers" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Recommended Providers</h2>

  <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Allianz Care — Best for Croatia</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    German-headquartered with excellent European networks. Strong relationships with Croatian and broader EU hospitals. Moratorium underwriting option helps with pre-existing conditions. Competitive pricing for Europe-focused coverage. Ideal for retirees planning to stay primarily in Croatia and EU.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Cigna Global — Best Overall</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Global network with good European coverage. Guaranteed acceptance option for pre-existing conditions. Worldwide coverage for travel outside EU. Higher premiums than regional options but more comprehensive. Good for retirees who travel frequently or may return to the US.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">IMG Global — Best Value</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Lower premiums with adequate coverage. Flexible plan options. Pre-existing conditions evaluated case-by-case. Good choice for healthy retirees balancing cost and coverage. Network is smaller than Cigna or Allianz.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Croatian Local Options</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Croatia Osiguranje and other local insurers offer private coverage at €80-150/month. These cover Croatia and often EU. Age limits and acceptance criteria vary. Useful once established—usually not sufficient for initial residency applications for non-EU citizens.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Retiree Insurance Options"
    description="See actual costs for your age and situation. No obligation quotes."
    buttonText="Get Personalized Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <h2 id="healthcare-access" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Healthcare Access in Croatia</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Public Healthcare (HZZO)</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Croatia's public system (HZZO) provides universal coverage to residents. Quality varies by location—Split and Zagreb hospitals are good; smaller towns are basic. Wait times for specialists can be long. EU citizens can use EHIC/GHIC for temporary stays; residents enroll directly.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Private Healthcare</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Private clinics in Split and Zagreb offer faster access and higher-end service. Hospitals like Medikol, Poliklinika Sunce, and Vilim Svečnjak provide good care. For complex cases, Vienna (3 hours) and Munich (6 hours) are common evacuation destinations.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Pharmacies</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Pharmacies (ljekarne) are well-stocked. Many medications available without prescription that require one elsewhere. Generic medications are affordable. Chain pharmacies in cities keep regular hours; smaller town pharmacies may have limited hours.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Practical Considerations</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    English is widely spoken in tourist areas but less common in healthcare settings outside Zagreb. Having a Croatian speaker accompany you to medical appointments helps. Smaller coastal towns may require travel to Split or Zagreb for specialist care.
  </p>

  <h2 id="costs" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Cost Planning</h2>

  <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Total Healthcare Budget</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    For a 60-year-old retiree: international insurance ($320-480/month) for the initial period. After HZZO enrollment: public coverage (€50-80/month) plus optional international coverage for private options (€150-250/month) plus out-of-pocket (€30-50/month). Total post-HZZO: €230-380/month for comprehensive hybrid coverage.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Cost-Saving Strategies</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    <strong>HZZO-only:</strong> Once enrolled, HZZO covers most needs at €50-80/month. Add travel insurance for trips outside Croatia. <strong>High deductible international:</strong> Keep international coverage for catastrophic events only. <strong>Europe-only plans:</strong> Excluding Americas/Asia reduces premiums significantly.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Compare to Alternatives</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Croatia is 20-30% cheaper than Spain or Portugal for similar coverage. Similar to Greece. Significantly cheaper than Italy or France. For budget-conscious retirees, Croatia offers Mediterranean lifestyle at Eastern European prices—now with full EU convenience.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 mb-8">
    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Is Croatia suitable for year-round retirement?</h3>
      <p>Coastal Croatia has mild winters (5-10°C) and warm summers. It's pleasant year-round but quieter October-April. Inland and northern Croatia have colder winters. Most retirees choose the coast. Some split time—Croatia summers, elsewhere winters.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Do I need to speak Croatian?</h3>
      <p>In tourist areas (Dubrovnik, Split, Hvar), English works well. In daily life and healthcare, Croatian helps significantly. It's a Slavic language—challenging for English speakers. Many retirees manage with English plus basic Croatian phrases. Translation apps help.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">How does HZZO work for foreigners?</h3>
      <p>Legal residents can voluntarily enroll in HZZO by paying monthly contributions (€50-80). This provides access to public hospitals and clinics. Quality is variable—good in cities, basic in rural areas. Wait times for specialists can be long. Many use HZZO plus supplemental private coverage.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Can I use my EHIC/GHIC in Croatia?</h3>
      <p>Yes, since Croatia is EU/Schengen. EU citizens can use EHIC for temporary stays. It covers emergency and necessary care but not routine care or repatriation. For long-term residence, proper health insurance or HZZO enrollment is required.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">What if I need specialized treatment?</h3>
      <p>For complex conditions (cancer, cardiac surgery, transplants), Croatian options are limited. Vienna is the common evacuation destination—3 hours by car, excellent hospitals, German-speaking. Munich is also accessible. International insurance with evacuation coverage is important.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Which city is best for retirement?</h3>
      <p>Split offers the best balance: good healthcare facilities, established expat community, excellent climate, historic charm, and reasonable costs. Dubrovnik is beautiful but expensive and crowded in summer. Smaller towns (Rovinj, Zadar, Šibenik) are cheaper but have fewer services. Zagreb has best healthcare but cold winters.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready to Retire in Croatia?"
    description="Get insurance that meets residency requirements and covers you long-term."
    buttonText="Get Your Croatia Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <p class="text-sm text-neutral-500 mt-12">
    This information is for educational purposes. Residency requirements, insurance options, and healthcare access rules change. Verify current requirements with Croatian authorities. Consider consulting with an immigration lawyer familiar with Croatian procedures for your specific situation. Last updated: May 2026.
  </p>
</PageShell>
